üëÜWisconsin Elections Commission (WEC) Update
In my last e-update, I mentioned the letter sent to WEC‚Äôs Administrator Meagan Wolfe, asking for information on Wisconsin‚Äôs election databases and voter rolls. A response was received from Meagan Wolfe and I appreciate the timeliness and thoroughness to the letter, but the accuracy of the database is still in question.

We now know that Knowledge Services is the vendor who manages IT for WEC. The application programming interface (API) from WEC to other entities is not to be shared with any nonprofits, political entities or other parties, yet we have found the existence of a handheld app with a backdoor into WEC. So was the WEC site hacked?

The Electronic Registration Information Center (ERIC) is denying the request because of its membership privacy agreement. This limits information to the public about what voter data ERIC approves for the clerks. 

I voted for ERIC with the understanding that we would eliminate double-voting within¬†and outside of Wisconsin, yet a year later, member states¬†still had not fulfilled the ERIC double-voting¬†agreement. While the concept of ERIC is great,¬†the length of time to get comparative data leads to questions about its value. The accuracy of the voter list is imperative to our democracy and we will continue to review this technology to secure Wisconsin's faith in elections.

Colorado Activates Crisis Standards of Care for Emergency Medical Services Amid COVID-19 Surge, Staffing Shortages

üá∫üá∏@COVID19Up: Dr. Eric France, chief medical officer at the Colorado Department of Health and Environment, reactivated crisis standards of care for emergency medical services on Friday (Jan. 7) for the first time since April 2020 as hospital resources have become strained under a surge of COVID-19 patients.

"With increasing demands on hospitals and EMS, we need to make sure we can provide care to anyone who needs it immediately. Crisis standards of care help us to do that," CDHE said in a press release.

Under the new standards, only individuals with the "most severe" cases of COVID-19 should be transported for medical treatment.

Several factors can disqualify individuals with COVID-19 from being transported for emergency medical treatment, including the absence of high-risk medical history, oxygen saturation above 90%, and being under 60 years of age, according to CDHE crisis standards of care.

Additionally, the standards recommend EMS staff not transport COVID-19 patients who are in continuous cardiac arrest.
